%N A396831 a(n) is the n-th digit after the decimal point in the decimal expansion of the natural logarithm of n.
%C A396831 For n >= 2, log(n) is transcendental (by the Lindemann-Weierstrass theorem) and hence irrational, so its n-th decimal digit is well-defined; log(1) = 0 gives a(1) = 0.
%F A396831 a(n) = floor(10^n * (log(n) - floor(log(n)))) mod 10.
%e A396831 log(1) = 0.0000........., so a(1) = 0.
%e A396831 log(2) = 0.6931471805..., whose 2nd decimal digit is 9, so a(2) = 9.
%e A396831 log(5) = 1.6094379124..., whose decimal digits after the point are 6,0,9,4,3,..., so the 5th is 3 and a(5) = 3.
%o A396831 (Python)
%o A396831 from decimal import Decimal, getcontext
%o A396831 def a(n):
%o A396831     if n == 1: return 0
%o A396831     getcontext().prec = n + 50
%o A396831     return int(str(Decimal(n).ln()).split(".")[1][n-1])
%o A396831 print([a(n) for n in range(1, 100)])
%Y A396831 Cf. A002162 (log 2), A002391 (log 3), A016627 (log 4), A016628 (log 5), A016629 (log 6), A016630 (log 7), A016631 (log 8), A016632 (log 9), A002392 (log 10).
